# Main line and git habits

## GitHub branch rules (solo operator)

- **Direct push to `main`** is normal. If GitHub shows “must use pull request,”
  **bypass as admin** or **turn off PR-only protection** on `main` so tooling
  matches linear solo work (`docs/github-actions-family-contract.md` § Branch
  protection and solo maintenance).

## Default branch

- Treat **`main`** as the only long-lived integration branch in family repos.
- Do **not** create parallel long-lived lines (`develop`, `release/*`, personal integration branches) out of habit. Merge legacy lines into **`main`** and retire them when you can.

## When to create a branch (sparingly)

- **Default:** commit directly on **`main`** when the change is small or you own the repo—**do not** spin up a branch just to move fast.
- **Use a short-lived branch** only when there is a **clear reason**: risky experiment, long-running WIP you do not want on **`main`** yet, or you explicitly want an isolated diff for review. Name clearly (`fix/…`, `chore/…`).
- If you do use a branch: keep it short, merge to **`main`**, then **delete** the remote branch and **`git checkout main && git pull`**.

## If you open a PR (optional workflow)

1. Base the branch on current **`origin/main`**.
2. Run validation from `docs/pr-checklist.md`.
3. Fill **`.github/pull_request_template.md`** when the PR is cross-repo or release-shaped.
4. Prefer **squash merge** for noisy branches; **merge commit** when the commit story matters.

## After integrated work

- Update **`@dev/notes/roadmap/v2-roadmap-status.md`** or round notes when the change closes tracked family work.

## Agents and operators

- **Do not** create a new branch unless the user or the task clearly needs isolation. Prefer **`main`**.
